    "\n",
    "Almost all potentials are define through a set of scale density and radii (and a set of shape parameters if the parameterization calls for it) "
   ]

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {

   "source": [
    "# third party\n",
    "import astropy.units as u\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.style.use(\"/Users/juan/phd/matplotlib/jdefault.mplstyle\")\n",
    "\n",
    "import jax\n",
    "import jax.numpy as jnp\n",
    "from jax._src.config import config\n",
    "\n",
    "config.update(\"jax_enable_x64\", True)\n",
    "\n",
    "from dynamicAll import models"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Currently we have the following potentials implemented:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Hernquist\n",
    "- NFW\n",
    "- gNFW\n",
    "- Einasto\n",
    "- Plummer\n",
    "- Isochrone\n",
    "- Jaffe\n",
    "- Gaussian\n",
    "- King \n",
    "\n",
    "Below we'll showcase a few examples and how they are used as well as caveats you should be aware of -- which are mostly things about jax that you should be aware of."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Double Power Laws"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Hernquist"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Herquist Parameters\n",
    "rhos = 1.0\n",
    "\n",
    "rs = 2\n",
    "hernquist_params = {\"rhos\": rhos, \"rs\": rs}\n",
    "\n",
    "hernquist = models.Hernquist(**hernquist_params)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Jaffe"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# rhos = 6.4e4\n",
    "# rs = 1.0\n",
    "jaffe_params = {\"rhos\": rhos, \"rs\": rs}\n",
    "\n",
    "jaffe = models.Jaffe(**jaffe_params)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Plummer\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Note: \n",
    "I've tried to keep naming schemes as initializations as consistent as possible.\n",
    "Almost every potential is by default initialized with some scale density and radius \"rhos\", and \"rs\" respectively. However some models are defined in terms of their mass and scale radius so you should be aware of the initialization parameters for each potential. There are alternative initialization (see the Documentation of each potential to see the alternative initializations).\n",
    "\n",
    "An example of this is the Plummer sphere where its usually defined in terms of its total mass and scale radius"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# M = 1e3\n",
    "# # rs = 1.0\n",
    "# plummer_params = {\"M\": M, \"rs\": rs}\n",
    "# plummer = models.Plummer(**plummer_params)\n",
    "# print(plummer._rhos)\n",
    "# Altenative initialization\n",
    "\n",
    "# rhos = plummer._rhos  # use the scale radius from the previous model\n",
    "alt_init_params = {\"rhos\": rhos, \"rs\": rs}\n",
    "plummer = models.Plummer.from_scale_density_radius(**alt_init_params)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Navaro-Frenk-White (NFW)\n",
    "\n",
    "Note: This model has several ways of initializing it. \n",
    "\n",
    "from \n",
    "- a scale mass and radius --this is how it's defined in [Gala](http://gala.adrian.pw/en/latest/api/gala.potential.potential.NFWPotential.html)\n",
    "- $M_{\\Delta}$ and a concentration parameter where $M_{\\Delta}$ is the mass enclosed within a radius $\\Delta$ times the critical density of the universe and the concentration parameter is the ratio of $r_{\\Delta}$ to the scale radius.\n",
    "\n",
    "I'll add more initializations if they're relevant.\n",
    "\n",
    "See the documentation for more details"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# model parameters\n",
    "# NFW\n",
    "# rhos = 6.4e4  # scale density in Msun/kpc^3\n",
    "# rs = 1.0  # scale radius in kpc\n",
    "nfw = models.NFW(rhos, rs)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

    "hz_hernquist = models.HernquistZhao(rhos, rs, 1, 1, 4)\n",
    "hz_jaffe = models.HernquistZhao(rhos, rs, 2, 1, 4)"
   ]

    "print(f\"Jaffe:     total mass =  {jaffe._M:.2e} Msun\")\n",
    "print(f\"NFW:       total mass =  {nfw._M:.2e} Msun\")\n",
    "print(f\"Plummer:   total mass =  {plummer._M:.2e} Msun\")"

  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note: The mass for NFW profile diverges as $r \\to \\infty$ so a cut off radius is needed to define a \"total mass\".\n",
    "There is a default paramter rlim that is set to 'r200' which is the radius at which the mean density is 200 times the critical density of the universe.\n",
    "However you can set this to any value you like.\n",
    "This will be the case for all potentials that diverge at large radii i.e. all density profiles in which $\\rho(r)\\sim r^{c}$ for $c \\le -3$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Depending on your needs it might be convenient to define your potential through a concentration parameter, c and $\\rm M_{200}$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Binned Power Laws\n",
    "\n",
    "If you've used Gravsphere you may want to use the same scheme for the potential. Its essentially a broken power law with more breaks then usual and without the smooothing factor as in the Hernquist-Zhao Model.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\rho(r) = \\rho_{s} \n",
    "\\begin{cases}\n",
    "    \\left(\\frac{r}{0.25R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\gamma} & r \\lt 0.25 R_{1/2} \\\\\n",
    "    \\left(\\frac{r}{0.5R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\beta}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{0.5 R_{1/2}}{0.25 R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\beta} & 0.25 R_{1/2} \\le r \\lt 0.5 R_{1/2} \\\\\n",
    "    \\left(\\frac{r}{R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\delta}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{R_{1/2}}{0.5 R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\delta}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{0.5 R_{1/2}}{0.25 R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\beta} & 0.5 R_{1/2} \\le r \\lt R_{1/2} \\\\\n",
    "    \\left(\\frac{r}{2R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\sigma}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{2 R_{1/2}}{R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\sigma}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{R_{1/2}}{0.5 R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\delta}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{0.5 R_{1/2}}{0.25 R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\beta}  & R_{1/2} \\le r \\lt 2 R_{1/2} \\\\\n",
    "    \\left(\\frac{r}{4R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\alpha}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{4 R_{1/2}}{2 R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\alpha}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{2 R_{1/2}}{R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\sigma}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{R_{1/2}}{0.5 R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\delta}\n",
    "        \\left(\\frac{0.5 R_{1/2}}{0.25 R_{1/2}}\\right)^{\\beta}  & r \\ge 2 R_{1/2} \\\\\n",
    "\\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "Where i've explicitly left terms uncanceled to show the reason they're there and to make it easier to show how to generalize it to more breaks inline with how the code is written."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "binnedpl = models.PowerLaws(\n",
    "    rhos=1e7, R_half=1.0, gamma=-1.0, beta=-2.0, delta=-3.0, sigma=-4.0, alpha=-5.0\n",
    ")"
   ]
